How Islamology stepped out of French academia's shadows after the 2015 jihadist attacks
description: Once a jewel of French research, Islamology began to decline in the 1980s, but the 2015 attacks forced authorities to refocus their efforts in this field of knowledge. Although the discipline has since experienced something of a revival, its recovery remains fragile, both as an academic subject and a highly political issue.

The last-minute fight to save Gaza's ancient archaeological treasures
description: Amid the vast destruction of the war, a small group of determined individuals fought to save Gaza's archaeological heritage. On September 10, they secured a few hours' reprieve from the Israeli army before a storage depot filled with artifacts was bombed to perform a delicate evacuation – the result of intense, high-level negotiations.

headline: Angoulême seeks an alternative to its ailing comics festival
description: The central French town has launched an alternative project of cultural offerings, aiming to calm the discontent of local shopkeepers and service providers, who are seeing substantial economic returns evaporate.

headline: Kikuo Ibe's quest to build the unbreakable watch
description: Forty-two years after inventing the first indestructible watch, the Casio G-Shock, the Japanese engineer continues to inspire. As part of a European tour, he stopped in France to meet his fans.

headline: Buyers of underage sex are rarely prosecuted: 'We are at ground zero of the criminal justice response'
description: The French justice system estimates that 15,000 girls under the age of 18 are sexually exploited in France. The criminal response has focused on dismantling pimping networks, even though clients can also face criminal prosecution for the rape of minors when the victims are under 15 years old.
byline: Lorraine de Foucher ,  Lucie Soullier and  Thomas Saintourens

description: Statements by General Fabien Mandon and President Emmanuel Macron's announcements about a voluntary national service have raised questions about a scenario that, until recently, seemed unimaginable.

headline: Filippo Sorcinelli, the man who dresses the pope
description: The Italian designer is one of the Vatican's preferred tailors. At 50, he has dressed the last three popes, including Leo XIV. Catholic and gay, he has patiently – and indulgently – observed the slow evolution of the Church.

headline: Andriy Yermak's resignation shocks Europe, but suits the US
description: With Volodymyr Zelensky's top aide stepping down, the EU loses a key interlocutor in Kyiv at a pivotal moment in peace talks. The Trump administration, by contrast, seems ready to leverage the crisis to push its own priorities.
byline: Philippe Jacqué,  Philippe Ricard and  Piotr Smolar
